title: Copyedit 0709
body:
Hey @summerofgeorge! My editor has wrapped up her first round of Jupyter Notebook edits, yay! :-) Let me see if I can semi organize these thoughts for you: 
- This round, she worked on DA, DS, and PM (though you don't have to worry about PM, she just applied her changes across all three). In DA and DS, she worked on the files in Python I and a few in Python II. 
- We still have a bunch more to go, but I'd love to get your eyes on a few of the changes before we continue on. (You definitely don't have to review everything -- I'd recommend just spot-checking a few files to get a sense. But you can also review them all if you'd like!) 
- I'd also like to get your blessing before we merge this first round of Notebook commits -- next time, you don't need to review, unless you want to. 
- I've also added a couple of comments to the files, too, which you'll see. 

Lmk if you have any questions, thanks so much for all your help with this!

title: Make statistical tests in Pandas prep "optional"
body:
@emetozar Here's an interesting one, a student caught that the statistical testing part of the Pandas prep is not explained, that's because in DA students already know it. And to try to explain it would take a whole module :)  So what I did in this file was mark it as "optional" so that it's still there.  Thoughts on this? https://github.com/Thinkful-Ed/data-science/issues/807  

We would need to tweak the drills a bit to not ask about this part of the checkpoint but that's not a problem.

title: updated gradient boost metrics for easier understanding
body:
original comment : " This guided example doesn't really explain the errors tables, does not provide an example of how to assess the performance of the model, nor does it discuss ways to tune the parameters of the model. Too much is left for the student to discover on her own. Relying on the two 45-minute sessions with the mentor to cover all of this, along with all the questions about executing the code in Python, is quite unreasonable."

section: https://courses.thinkful.com/dsbc-boosting-models-v1/checkpoint/3

change: changed the metric to confusion matrix since it will be more understandable and more widely accepted by industry.  This is a classifier example afterall.  add a link to show where they can find where to tune parameters for Gradient Boost Model.

23833.87 is the coefficient of is_smoker. Its not clear how we can read anything about gender from that single coefficient.
